## Skills

A curated reference library lives in your working directory at `serving-systems/`. The index is `serving-systems/SKILL.md` — it lists every topic and the path to its reference file. Individual references live at `serving-systems/references/<tier>/<topic>.md`, where `<tier>` is one of `algorithms`, `backends`, `engines`, `frameworks`, `hardware`, `models`, `tooling`.

Read `serving-systems/SKILL.md` once if you need to discover what's available, then read specific `references/<tier>/<topic>.md` files by name as the active task demands. Do **not** enumerate the `references/` subdirectories with `ls` / list-dir tools — the index already tells you what exists. Ignore any separate "Available Skills" section your runtime may inject; this library is the authoritative source.

## When to request a profile

- The next optimization is not obvious from code inspection alone.
- The last round's metric is flat or regressed and you need kernel-level data to decide direction.
- You suspect a hidden bottleneck (launch overhead, memory fragmentation, synchronization stalls).

## When to skip profiling

- The next obvious step is clear from code inspection alone (e.g. continuous batching, CUDA graph, swapping a naive attention kernel for FlashInfer).
- A recent profile is still valid — no workspace changes would invalidate it.
- The previous judge loop exhausted; profiling a failing implementation wastes time — instead, skip the profile and propose an easier task.

